{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17647381","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17647381"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:45:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:45:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18247"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18247","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18247"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.56,0.3,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10961"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73936"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10961","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10961"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18247"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59412"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1259"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7418"},{"type":"tags","id":"7422"},{"type":"tags","id":"7431"},{"type":"tags","id":"11439"},{"type":"tags","id":"11440"},{"type":"tags","id":"11441"},{"type":"tags","id":"11442"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25470"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25473"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27574"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73936"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 12-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with a limp that has been worsening over the past few months. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His gait is antalgic, and there is a noticeable shortening of the affected leg. Hip examination reveals limited abduction and internal rotation. An X-ray of the pelvis is performed, showing a decreased angle between the head and shaft of the femur on the affected side.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the anatomical change in coxa vara?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Distal femur deviates medially","Proximal femur deviates laterally","Femoral head is displaced anteriorly","Femoral neck is elongated","Greater trochanter is positioned inferiorly"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDistal femur deviates medially\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct description of the anatomical change in coxa vara. In this condition, the angle between the head and shaft of the femur is reduced, causing the distal femur to deviate medially. This can lead to a limp and altered biomechanics of the hip joint.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProximal femur deviates laterally\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as coxa vara involves a medial deviation of the distal femur, not a lateral deviation of the proximal femur.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFemoral head is displaced anteriorly\u003C/strong\u003E is not characteristic of coxa vara. This description might be more relevant to conditions affecting the hip joint itself, such as hip dysplasia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFemoral neck is elongated\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. In coxa vara, the issue is with the angle of the femoral neck, not its length.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGreater trochanter is positioned inferiorly\u003C/strong\u003E is not a feature of coxa vara. The position of the greater trochanter is not directly affected by the angle of the femoral neck in this condition.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Coxa vara is a condition where the angle between the head and shaft of the femur is reduced, leading to a medial deviation of the distal femur.","This condition can lead to altered gait and increased stress on the hip joint.","Coxa vara can be congenital or acquired due to conditions such as rickets or trauma."],"references":["Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2018). Textbook of Orthopaedics, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2018). Textbook of Anatomy Abdomen and Lower Limb; Volume II (Vol. 2). Elsevier Health Sciences","Cantrell AJ, Imonugo O, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Leg Bones. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537024/","Raftery A. General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System. Ann R Coll Surg Engl. 2006 Jul;88(4):425. doi: 10.1308/003588406X114802d. PMCID: PMC1964629"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59412"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18247"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59412","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59412"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-24T08:06:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-24T08:07:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10961"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73936"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},